        name='retrieve_information',
        args='{"prompt": "What does the filing say about capital expenditure plans, AI infrastructure buildout, spending expectations, or investment plans for 2026 and beyond in {{spacex_s1}}? Look for any forward-looking statements about capex, data center construction, GPU purchases, or infrastructure investment."}',
        parsed_args={
            'prompt': 'What does the filing say about capital expenditure plans, AI infrastructure buildout, spending expectations, or investment plans for 2026 and beyond in {{spacex_s1}}? Look for any forward-looking statements about capex, data center construction, GPU purchases, or infrastructure investment.'
        }
    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided excerpts from the filing, here are the key forward-looking statements and disclosures regarding capital expenditure, infrastructure investment, and future plans for 2026 and beyond.\n\n### **1. AI Infrastructure & Data Center Investment**\n*   **Substantial and Increasing CapEx:** The company states it "expect[s] to increase our capital expenditures substantially in the future" and has "made and intend to continue to make substantial capital expenditures to support the growth of our AI products." This includes costs for third-party GPUs, manufacturing its own GPUs, and constructing/leasing/expanding data centers.\n*   **Multi-Year Investment Horizon:** "We expect a multi-year investment horizon before these deployments translate into sustained positive AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA." Capital expenditures for AI are expected to "scale as quickly as we are able to deploy power and compute."\n*   **Recent and Future Commitments:**\n    *   A five-year lease for AI infrastructure hardware valued at **$6.587 billion** (April 2026).\n    *   A cloud services agreement for compute capacity with Anthropic through May 2029 (May 2026).\n    *   An asset purchase agreement for mobile gas turbines for **~$2 billion** to help power data centers (April 2026, expected to close May 2026).\n*   **Construction-in-Progress:** A significant portion of "Property, plant, and equipment" is classified as "Construction-in-progress," which grew from $4.6 billion at year-end 2025 to **$14.045 billion** at the end of Q1 2026.\n\n### **2. Capital Expenditure Trends & Expectations**\n*   **Historical Surge:** AI segment capital expenditures exploded from **$463 million** in 2023 to **$12.727 billion** in 2025.\n*   **Q1 2026 Acceleration:** In just the first quarter of 2026, AI CapEx was **$7.723 billion**, already representing over 60% of the full year 2025 total, indicating a rapidly accelerating pace.\n*   **Funding Strategy:** The company "plan[s] to access a range of debt and equity financing solutions... to fund future investments in growth and to maintain strong liquidity."\n\n### **3. Specific Infrastructure Focus Areas**\n*   **Terrestrial Data Centers:** The primary driver of the massive increase in AI CapEx is "investments in the rapid expansion of our terrestrial data centers, including the development, construction, and equipping of new facilities and supporting infrastructure."\n*   **GPU & Compute Hardware:** Investments include "obtaining third-party GPUs, manufacturing our own GPUs" and building "AI compute infrastructure."\n*   **Power & Energy:** The turbine acquisition is specifically to "help provide power to the Company\'s data centers."\n\n### **4. Long-Term Vision: Orbital AI & Starship**\n*   **Starship as an Enabler:** Starship development is framed as a cost-reducer that will "establish a scalable path to creating the infrastructure of the future, such as **orbital AI compute**."\n*   **Goal of Dramatic Cost Reduction:** The filing expects Starship to "reduce the cost to reach orbit by 99% or more relative to the historical average launch cost."\n\n### **5. Cautionary Statements & Risks**\n*   **Profitability Warning:** The company explicitly warns that it "may choose to increase or accelerate the pace of any of these investments at any time, which could result in periods of **reduced profitability or increased losses** as we prioritize long-term growth over near-term financial performance."\n*   **Uncertain Returns:** There "can be no assurance that the returns on our AI investments will be adequate to justify the capital deployed."\n*   **Nascent Market Risk:** The "commercial value proposition of frontier AI models remains largely unproven," and the AI segment "has incurred significant operating losses since inception."\n\n**In summary, the filing presents a picture of an aggressive, multi-year investment cycle focused on terrestrial AI data centers and compute hardware, funded through significant financing, with the explicit goal of capturing a large market opportunity while accepting a near-term drag on profitability. The long-term vision ties this to cost-effective space launch capability (Starship) for future orbital infrastructure.**',
